{{Infobox News event |image={{Location map|Turkey|width=200 |float=center |caption= |mark=Cross.svg |marksize=6 |label=Mt. Zigana, Gümüşhane |position=bottom |lat_deg=40 |lat_min=38 |lat_sec=56.4 |lat_dir=N |lon_deg=039 |lon_min=23 |lon_sec=34.08 |lon_dir=E }} |caption=Mt. Zigana in relation to Turkey |date= {{start date|2009|01|25}} |time= 11:15 [[Eastern European Time|EET]] (09:15 [[UTC]]) |place= [[Mount Zigana]], [[Gümüşhane Province]], [[Turkey]] |casualties1=11 dead |casualties2=1 injured }}
The '''2009 Zigana avalanche''' was an [[avalanche]] that occurred on 25 January at around 11:15 local time (09:15 [[UTC]]) on [[Mount Zigana]], [[Gümüşhane Province]] in north-eastern [[Turkey]]. It struck a group of 17 hikers at a height of {{convert|2200|m|ft|abbr=on}} near the site of a small ski resort. The snow mass dragged the hikers about {{convert|1000|m|ft|abbr=on}} into a valley.<ref name="cnn">{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/WORLD/europe/01/25/turkey.avalanche/index.html?iref=topnews|title=Avalanche kills 10 at Turkish ski resort|publisher=[[CNN]]|accessdate=2009-01-25 | date=January 25, 2009}}</ref> Ten people were killed, one person was rescued with injuries and another one died in hospital while five others survived without injuries.<ref name="hdn">{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/english/domestic/10853072.asp |work=Hürriyet Daily News |title=Zigana avalanche kills 11 mountain trekkers |accessdate=February 18, 2009 }}</ref>
Teams from civilian defense and other public administrations rushed to the scene for the rescue of the victims from a sports club in [[Trabzon]] after local gendarmerie was notified of the incident. Also a team of AKUT, a voluntary disaster search and rescue organization, travelled from Trabzon to the location, to assess the situation and to offer any help and assistance necessary.
[[Nasuh Mahruki]], the first Turkish [[Mt. Everest]] summiter and the head of AKUT, said that "the accident was a walking group accident, not a mountain climbing accident. It is apparent that they hit the road without an avalanche test. It is very difficult for 16 to 17 people to remain under an avalanche."<ref name="hdn"/>
