{{Infobox Cloud |name=Cirrus duplicatus |image location= |image name= |abbreviation=Ci du |symbol=CH_1.png |genus=Cirrus (''curl of hair'') |species= |variety=duplicatus (''multiple layers'') |altitude_m=Above 5,000 |altitude_ft=Above 16,500 |appearance=two or more overlapping layers<ref>{{cite web|title=Cirrus|url=http://www.clouds-online.com/cloud_atlas/cirrus/cirrus.htm|work=Cloud Atlas|accessdate=13 July 2011|author=Wolken Online}}</ref> |precipitation=No}} '''Cirrus duplicatus''' is a variety of [[cirrus cloud]]. The name ''cirrus duplicatus'' is derived from [[Latin]], meaning "double".<ref>{{cite web|title=duplicatus|url=http://latinlookup.com/word/18551/duplicatus|accessdate=13 July 2011|author=Latin Lookup}}</ref> The duplicatus variety of cirrus clouds occurs when there are at least two layers of cirrus clouds. Most of the time, occurrences of [[cirrus fibratus]] and [[cirrus uncinus]] are in the duplicatus form.<ref>{{cite web|last=Callanan|first=Martin|title=Cirrus duplicatus|url=http://nephology.eu/cirrus/cirrus-duplicatus|work=International Cloud Atlas|publisher=nephology.eu|accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref> Like [[stratus cloud]]s, cirrus clouds are often seen in the duplicatus form.<ref>{{cite book|last=Dunlop|first=Storm|title=The weather identification handbook|year=2003|publisher=Lyons Press|location=Guilford, Conn.|isbn=1-58574-857-9|pages=58|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BR2ft4G5TgQC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA58#v=onepage&q=duplicatus&f=false|edition=1st Lyons Press|accessdate=13 July 2011}}</ref>
