[[File:Puu Oo - Beach 1988.jpg|thumb|400x400px|A littoral cone lies on the right, on top of the cliffs]]'''Littoral cones''' are a form of [[volcanic cone]]. They form from the interaction between [[lava flows]] and water. [[Steam explosion]]s fragment the lava and the fragments can pile up and form a cone. Such cones usually form on [[aa lava]] flows, and typically require large lava flows to form. They have been found on [[Hawaii]] and elsewhere.
Littoral cones are semicircular cones which are breached in the direction of the [[lava flow]] that created them. They are formed by mounds of [[clast]]s that appear like cones without a [[Volcanic crater|crater]].{{sfn|Fisher|1968|p=839}} Littoral cones are constructed by [[volcanic ash]], [[lava bomb]]s and [[lapilli]].<ref name="FisherSchmincke2012" /> Their component material is usually poorly sorted and can feature agglutinated structures and layering.<ref name="Green1982" /> Sometimes [[spatter cone|spatter]]-fed lava flows occur on such cones.<ref name="GreeleyFagents2001" /> They are formed by degassed [[hyaloclastite]].{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=477}}{{sfn|Fisher|1968|p=839}} The most common form found on Hawaii involves two semicircles on both sides of the lava flow that generated them;{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=472}} some such cones on Hawaii form a complete rim with diameters of {{convert|200|-|400|m}}.{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=471}} Puu Ki on Hawaii has nested craters on top of a [[lava tube]].<ref name="Walker1993" /> Typically such cones are not larger than {{convert|800|m}} wide and {{convert|75|m}} high.<ref name="Green1982" /> Other smaller cones on Hawaii have diameters of {{convert|40|m}} and heights reaching {{convert|15|m}}.{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=478}}
Littoral cones not primary volcanic [[Volcano|vents]] and distinguishing between a littoral cone and a primary vent can be difficult.<ref name="Green1982" /> A littoral cone forms when [[lava]] flows from land into water. Interaction between the water and the lava leads to steam explosions. These explosions throw lava fragments into the air; under favourable circumstances these fragments pile up on land and form a cone.{{sfn|Moore|Ault|1965|p=3}} This activity may resemble that of [[Hawaiian eruption|fire fountaining]].{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=478}} Repeated phases of magma-water mixing lead to the formation of bedded deposits.<ref name="FisherSchmincke2012" /> The steam explosions can lead to the formation of [[Limu o Pele|Pele's hair]].<ref name="MattoxMangan1997" /> The forming lava flows need to be sufficiently large;{{sfn|Moore|Ault|1965|p=9}} the minimum size of lava flows that have formed such cones in Hawaii is {{convert|50,000,000|yd3|order=flip}}.{{sfn|Moore|Ault|1965|p=10}} Of these, about 5-6% of their volume is converted to fragments.<ref name="Green1982" /> Usually littoral cones are formed by aa lava as their fragmented nature allows ideal water-lava interactions, but [[pahoehoe]] and intermediary lavas can also form littoral cones.{{sfn|Fisher|1968|p=861}} Other properties such as the speed of the lava flow and the structure of the flow front also influence the formation of littoral cones.{{sfn|Moore|Ault|1965|p=10}} Larger lava flow rates generate larger cones.{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=481}} In some littoral cones on Hawaii that were formed by pahoehoe lava flows, the collapse of a [[lava bench]] and subsequent steam explosions formed the cones instead.{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=471}} [[Pyroclastic flow]]s can also form littoral cones, one such cone has been found on [[Lombok]] and formed during the [[1257 Samalas eruption]].<ref name="Vidal2015" />
[[Pseudocrater]]s and littoral cones have been found on [[Iceland]], Hawaii, [[Cerro Azul (Ecuador volcano)|Cerro Azul]] in the [[Galápagos Islands|Gálapagos Islands]],{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=471}} [[Deception Island]], [[Antarctica]],<ref name="Smellie2004" /> and [[Medicine Lake Volcano]], [[California]].<ref name="MedicineLake" /> Sometimes the words "pseudocrater" and "littoral cone" are used as synonyms.<ref name="Einarsson1982" /> Littoral cones are usually quickly removed by [[Coastal erosion|sea erosion]]; thus littoral cones are rare.{{sfn|Moore|Ault|1965|p=3}}
Prehistorical littoral cones have been found on the coast of Hawaii, where the volcanoes [[Mauna Loa]] and [[Kilauea]] face the sea. They were named "littoral cones" by Wentworth in 1938.{{sfn|Fisher|1968|p=842}} About 50 large cones are found on these two volcanoes and only three of them were formed during historical times; no such cones have been found on the other Hawaiian volcanoes.{{sfn|Moore|Ault|1965|p=3}} The [[Puu Oo]] and [[Mauna Ulu]] eruptions of Kilauea have also formed small littoral cones.{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=471}}
Examples of littoral cones include Sand Hills (1840 eruption) on Kilauea in Hawaii,{{sfn|Fisher|1968|p=841}} 'Au'au, Nā Pu'u a Pele, Pu'u Hou (1868 eruption) and Pu'u Kī (eruption 1300 years ago) at Mauna Loa on Hawaii,{{sfn|Jurado-Chichay|Rowland|Walker|1996|p=472}} a cone close to [[Isabela Island (Ecuador)|Villamil]] at [[Sierra Negra]], Galapagos,<ref name="ReynoldsGeist1995" /> Eldborg (1800 years ago) at [[Hengill]] on Iceland,<ref name="StevensonMitchell2009" /> a cone in the Winter Water unit of the [[Columbia Plateau|Columbia Plateau Basalts]], [[Oregon]],<ref name="Columbia" /> a cone at [[Becharof Lake]], [[Alaska]],<ref name="Lu2002" /> Burilan and Devil Rock on [[Gaua]],<ref name="Metrich2016" /> and Ponta de Ferraria (eruption 840 ± 60 years ago) on [[São Miguel Island]], [[Azores]].<ref name="LimaNunes2016" /> The Speedwell Vent in [[Derbyshire]], [[United Kingdom]] may also be a littoral cone of [[Carboniferous]] age.<ref name="CheshireBell1976" /> [[Pleistocene]] littoral cones may also exist in [[Lake Tahoe]], California.<ref name="Tahoe" />
